The MÃ¶bius function of permutations with an indecomposable lower bound

Robert Brignall, David Marchant

School of Mathematics and Statistics
The Open University, Milton Keynes, MK7 6AA, UK
Abstract

We show that the MÃ¶bius function of an interval in a permutation poset where the lower bound is sum (resp. skew) indecomposable depends solely on the sum (resp. skew) indecomposable permutations contained in the upper bound, and that this can simplify the calculation of the MÃ¶bius sum. For increasing oscillations, we give a recursion for the MÃ¶bius sum which only involves evaluating simple inequalities.

The study of the MÃ¶bius function in the permutation poset was introduced by WilfÂ [9]. The first result in this area was by Sagan and VatterÂ [4], who determined the MÃ¶bius function on intervals of layered permutations. Many results for Î¼â€‹[Ïƒ,Ï€]ğœ‡ğœğœ‹\mu[\sigma,\pi] have been obtained by considering ways in which Ïƒğœ\sigma can be found in Ï€ğœ‹\pi, which we call an embedding of Ïƒğœ\sigma in Ï€ğœ‹\pi, although typically only some of the embeddings (â€œnormal embeddingsâ€) are counted. In this paper we show that the MÃ¶bius function on intervals with a sum indecomposable lower bound depends only on the sum indecomposable permutations contained in the upper bound. We provide a weighting function that determines which sum indecomposable permutations contribute to the MÃ¶bius sum. We then consider increasing oscillations. For these permutations, we show how we can find all of the permutations that contribute to the MÃ¶bius sum by applying simple numeric inequalities, which leads to a fast polynomial algorithm for determining the MÃ¶bius function.

We start with some essential definitions and notation in SectionÂ 2, then in SectionÂ 3 we provide a number of preliminary lemmas.
